d medical experiences of the poor largely in their own words, Sickness, medical welfare and the English poor offers a comprehensive reinterpretation of the so-called crisis of the Old Poor Law from the later eighteenth century. The sick poor became an insistent presence in the lives of officials and parishes and the (largely positive) way that communities responded to their dire needs must cause us to rethink the role and character of the poor law.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 1, No poverty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPoorxMedical carezEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aPoorxMedical carezEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aNo poverty.  aill-health.  amedical welfare.  apaternalism.  apoor law.1 aKing, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packagez978311128277040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612901740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129017423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129017/original  a978-3-11-128277-0  Manchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packageb2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles